<subSubSection id="C3576533FFD87B1978B7E764FD2AA87C" pageId="22" pageNumber="328" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BF236B8FFD87B1978B7E764FD2AA87C" blockId="22.[151,1437,1333,1614]" pageId="22" pageNumber="328">
<emphasis id="B939EAAAFFD87B1978B7E764FEEBAB37" bold="true" box="[151,274,1333,1359]" pageId="22" pageNumber="328">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species was described from a single male from 
<collectingCountry id="F35A7628FFD87B197B7FE764FC49AB37" box="[863,944,1333,1359]" name="Poland" pageId="22" pageNumber="328">Poland</collectingCountry>
. It closely resembles 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D3BFFD87B197CBEE767FA60AB28" authority="(Wood)" baseAuthorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[1182,1433,1333,1360]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrescens">
<emphasis id="B939EAAAFFD87B197CBEE767FAC3AB37" box="[1182,1338,1334,1359]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="328">M. nigrescens</emphasis>
(Wood)
</taxonomicName>
. Indeed, the hypopygia are very alike. Unfortunately, the front legs of the 
<typeStatus id="54F6881AFFD87B197BD0E708FBABAB0B" box="[1008,1106,1369,1395]" pageId="22" pageNumber="328">holotype</typeStatus>
were damaged and only the incomplete front tarsus of one leg remained. The specimens from 
<collectingCountry id="F35A7628FFD87B197B4BE72CFC2AABEF" box="[875,979,1405,1431]" name="Denmark" pageId="22" pageNumber="328">Denmark</collectingCountry>
allow a clearer distinction. Thus, the fore tarsus of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D3BFFD87B1978DEE7F3FE62ABC3" baseAuthorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[254,411,1442,1467]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrescens">
<emphasis id="B939EAAAFFD87B1978DEE7F3FE62ABC3" box="[254,411,1442,1467]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="328">M. nigrescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has posterodorsal hair palisades on segments 1 to 4 only (
<figureCitation id="13762A3DFFD87B197C07E7F0FB73ABC3" box="[1063,1162,1441,1467]" captionStart="FIGURES 169–172" captionStartId="23.[151,264,920,944]" captionTargetBox="[324,1263,183,893]" captionTargetId="figure-32@23.[324,1263,181,896]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 169–172. Megaselia nigricia Disney &amp; Durska and M. nigresens (Woiod). Postpedicels 169, of M. nigricia; 170, of M. nigrescens; Front tarsal segments 4 and 5 171, of M. nigricia; 172, of M. nigrescens" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4925251" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4925251/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="328">Fig. 172</figureCitation>
); whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D3BFFD87B197D3EE7F3FA64ABC3" box="[1310,1437,1442,1467]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigricia">
<emphasis id="B939EAAAFFD87B197D3EE7F3FA64ABC3" box="[1310,1437,1442,1467]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="328">M. nigricia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are present on all five segments (
<figureCitation id="13762A3DFFD87B197A6BE794FD56ABA7" box="[587,687,1477,1503]" captionStart="FIGURES 169–172" captionStartId="23.[151,264,920,944]" captionTargetBox="[324,1263,183,893]" captionTargetId="figure-32@23.[324,1263,181,896]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 169–172. Megaselia nigricia Disney &amp; Durska and M. nigresens (Woiod). Postpedicels 169, of M. nigricia; 170, of M. nigrescens; Front tarsal segments 4 and 5 171, of M. nigricia; 172, of M. nigrescens" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4925251" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4925251/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="328">Fig. 171</figureCitation>
). In addition, the postpedicels of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D3BFFD87B197C0EE797FB35ABA7" baseAuthorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[1070,1228,1478,1503]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrescens">
<emphasis id="B939EAAAFFD87B197C0EE797FB35ABA7" box="[1070,1228,1478,1503]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="328">M. nigrescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lack SPS vesicles (
<figureCitation id="13762A3DFFD87B197880E7B8FF06A87B" box="[160,255,1513,1539]" captionStart="FIGURES 169–172" captionStartId="23.[151,264,920,944]" captionTargetBox="[324,1263,183,893]" captionTargetId="figure-32@23.[324,1263,181,896]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 169–172. Megaselia nigricia Disney &amp; Durska and M. nigresens (Woiod). Postpedicels 169, of M. nigricia; 170, of M. nigrescens; Front tarsal segments 4 and 5 171, of M. nigricia; 172, of M. nigrescens" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4925251" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4925251/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="328">Fig. 170</figureCitation>
) but are present in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D3BFFD87B1979F7E7BBFDACA87B" box="[471,597,1514,1539]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigricia">
<emphasis id="B939EAAAFFD87B1979F7E7BBFDACA87B" box="[471,597,1514,1539]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="328">M. nigricia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="13762A3DFFD87B197A44E7B8FD3FA87C" box="[612,710,1513,1540]" captionStart="FIGURES 169–172" captionStartId="23.[151,264,920,944]" captionTargetBox="[324,1263,183,893]" captionTargetId="figure-32@23.[324,1263,181,896]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 169–172. Megaselia nigricia Disney &amp; Durska and M. nigresens (Woiod). Postpedicels 169, of M. nigricia; 170, of M. nigrescens; Front tarsal segments 4 and 5 171, of M. nigricia; 172, of M. nigrescens" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4925251" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4925251/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="328">Fig. 169</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
